Pipeline

This document summarizes the pipeline of this repository to validate Global Circulation Models (GCMs) from the Couple Model Inter-comparison Project (CMIP6) using ground stations from the Global Historical Climatology Network Daily (GHCNd) database. The pipeline is summarized in the figure below and is intended to be ran within the EVE cluster at UFZ Leipzig. Other set-ups are possible, given proper path specifications (see loadVariants() function). The pipeline relies mostly on the tidyverse, terra, and GHCNr packages. See env.yaml for the full virtual environment.

Example

library(terra)
library(GHCNr)
library(tidyverse)
source("scripts/variants.R")
source("scripts/continents.R")
source("scripts/tas.R")
source("scripts/stations.R")
terraOptions(progress = 0)

# time period and variable of interest
experiment <- "historical"  # 1850-2014 in CMIP6
variable <- "tas"           # average temperature

Load variants (aka ensemble members)

The start of the workflow is to load all the variants of one GCM. Variants are identified by four indices: r, i, p, and f. For instance, r1i1p1f1 is the variant almost always reported by all GCMs. The other variants distributed are different across GCMs. Load the variants with loadVariants(), which requires an input the name of the GCM (model), the experiment (e.g., “historical”), and the variable of interest (e.g., “tas”). The output of loadVariants() is a SpatRasterDataset of the variants with names the variant label (e.g., r1i1p1f1).

model <- "CMCC-ESM2"  # this GCM only reports one variant, `r1i1p1f1`

# load variants of the GCM
variants <- loadVariants(
  model,        
  "historical",
  "tas",
  dataDir = "data"
)

variants

Summarize GCM to annual values

The output of GCMs is usually monthly. Albeit this can be used for validation, it is easier (and perhaps more justified) to use annual summaries. The function annualTas() takes as input the SpatRasterDataset outputted from loadVarians() and return a SpatRasterDataset with the format and names, but with annual summaries.

# summarize to annual layers
a <- annualTas(variants)

# plot the first 4 years of the first (and only) variant
panel(
  a$`r1i1p1f1`[[1:4]],
  nc = 2,
  col = hcl.colors(100, "Spectral", rev = TRUE)
)

Obtain GHCNd data

For validation we will download and use the weather station data from the GHCNd database. Access to the GHCNd is performed via the GHCNd API through the R package GHCNr. This can be quite slow for areas with many stations and it might be better to download the weather station data before and independently from the validation script.

Once the GHCNd data is downloaded, the rasterizeStations() function create a raster from the station table with the same grid of the GCM output. The rasterization processes averages the values of the weather station data yearly and spatially within the same grid. Weather stations data that has less than 95% of the year covered is discarded, resulting in potentially non-continuous raster values.

# Data already downloaded to speed up.
# Check GHCNr package for how to get these data.
s <- read_csv("data/italy-stations.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)
it <- vect("data/italy.shp")

# rasterize stations
# 
# This is quite time-consuming and I saved the output
# of the commented lines below to speed it up.
# 
# ghcnd <- rasterizeStations(s, a[[1]])
# writeVector(ghcnd$vector, "data/ghcnd-vector.shp")
# writeRaster(ghcnd$raster, "data/ghcnd-raster.tif")
ghcnd <- list(
  vector = vect("data/ghcnd-vector.shp"),
  raster = rast("data/ghcnd-raster.tif")
)

# plot first four years
panel(
  crop(ghcnd$raster[[1:4]], it),
  nc = 2,
  col = hcl.colors(100, "Spectral", rev = TRUE),
  fun = \() {points(ghcnd$vector); lines(it)}
)

Combine GCM projections and GHCNd data

The function extractValues() combine the output of GCMs with the data from GHCNd. The rasterization of the weather station must be done using the GCM grid, as we have done previously. When validating another GCM, the rasterization needs to be performed again (see Validate another GCM section below).

vals <- extractValues(ghcnd, a)
# outfile <- stringr::str_glue("{experiment}-{variable}-{model}.csv")
# vals |> write_csv(file.path("data", outfile))

Validation

vals |>
  ggplot() +
  aes(GHCNd, `r1i1p1f1` - 273.15) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, linetype = "dashed") +
  scale_x_continuous("GHCNd data", breaks = seq(-10, 20, by = 5), limits = c(-10, 21)) +
  scale_y_continuous("GCM projection", breaks = seq(-10, 20, by = 5), limits = c(-10, 21)) +
  theme_classic()

sqrt(mean( (vals$GHCNd - vals$`r1i1p1f1` + 273.15)^2 ))
## [1] 4.449799

Validate another GCM

To validate another GCM for the same region and time period, we need to:

  1. Load the model variants for that GCMs.
  2. Rasterize (or download) again the GHCNd weather station data.
  3. Combine the GCM and GHCNd data.
  4. Perform again the validation test.
# change GCM
model <- "CAMS-CSM1-0"

# load variants
variants <- loadVariants(
  model,        # this GCM only reports one variant, `r1i1p1f1`
  "historical",
  "tas",
  dataDir = "data"
)

# summarize to annual 
a <- annualTas(variants)

# load GHCNd
ghcnd <- list(
  vector = vect("data/ghcnd-vector.shp"),
  raster = rast("data/ghcnd-raster.tif")
)

# you could run, as before:
# 
# s <- stations()
# ...
# ghcnd <- rasterizeStations()
# 
# but it is faster to rasterize ghcnd$vector again.
ghcnd$vector <- project(ghcnd$vector, crs(a[[1]]))
ghcnd$raster <- rasterize(ghcnd$vector, a[[1]][[1]], field = "tavg", by = "year", fun = "mean", na.rm = TRUE)

# extract values
#
# because this GCM has more three variants, the table will have
# three columns.
vals <- extractValues(ghcnd, a)

vals <- vals |>
  pivot_longer(
    cols = contains("i1p1"),
    names_to = "variant",
    values_to = "tavg"
  )

vals |>
  ggplot() +
  aes(GHCNd, tavg - 273.15, col = variant) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, linetype = "dashed") +
  scale_color_manual("Variant", values = c("dodgerblue4", "tomato", "gold3")) +
  scale_x_continuous("GHCNd data", breaks = seq(-10, 20, by = 5), limits = c(-10, 21)) +
  scale_y_continuous("GCM projection", breaks = seq(-10, 20, by = 5), limits = c(-10, 21)) +
  theme_classic()

# RMSE for the three variants
vals |>
  group_by(variant) |>
  summarize(
    RMSE = sqrt( mean((GHCNd - tavg + 273.15)^2) ),
    .groups = "drop"
  )
## # A tibble: 3 × 2
##   variant   RMSE
##   <chr>    <dbl>
## 1 r1i1p1f1  3.63
## 2 r1i1p1f2  3.63
## 3 r2i1p1f1  3.64
vals |>
  ggplot() +
  aes(tavg - 273.15, fill = variant) +
  geom_density(position = "identity", alpha = .25, col = "grey20") +
  scale_fill_manual("Variant", values = c("dodgerblue4", "tomato", "gold3")) +
  scale_x_continuous("GCM projection", breaks = seq(-10, 20, by = 5)) +
  scale_y_continuous("Density", expand = expansion(c(0, 0), c(0, .01))) +
  theme_classic()
